node.title: Is it possible to implement slope limiters in DG kernels?
node.bodyText:
Hello MOOSE Users,
I have previously implemented dislocation transport equations using DGKernels for advection.
These kernels were an extension of DGConvection with custom velocity directions
that depend on the crystallographic directions of my problem.
An example can be found here:
https://github.com/ngrilli/c_pfor_am/blob/main/src/dgkernels/DGAdvectionCoupled.C
Now, I would like to add a slope limiter to mitigate some of the oscillations
at sharp interfaces of the dislocation density variable.
I have read the finite volume code available,
such as FVAdvection and FVLimitedAdvection,
where slope limiters can be easily introduced.
I am asking whether it is possible to incorporate slope limiters into DGConvection
and if anyone has explored this. I could not find any examples of this approach
in the framework or modules.
I am at an early stage of this development and would appreciate your suggestion:
should I implement my previous transport laws into the FV framework,
or is there a simple way to retrofit my previous DG kernels with slope limiters?
I don't mind about the order of the variables because I previously used the DGKernels
with constant monomial variables, therefore it was behaving like FV anyway.
I am just looking for the easiest way to implement it.
Thank you very much in advance for your help.
Best Regards,
Nicolò

Hello
This has been done in the thermal hydraulics module for 1D flow.
look at SlopeReconstruction1DInterface and the RDG3EqnMaterial.
DGKernels are also used for this variable-area Euler equation implementation.
I dont think anyone has done this for DGConvection. @lindsayad if you've heard of this.

should I implement my previous transport laws into the FV framework,
I don't mind about the order of the variables because I previously used the DGKernels
with constant monomial variables, therefore it was behaving like FV anyway.

I would wager writing code in FV is easier than DG. We are pouring a lot of resources into FV. We have better success there than we have ever had with CG. DG has not been explored fully imo, and @lindsayad is exploring Hybridized DG in MOOSE currently
Guillaume

Thank you very much @GiudGiud
I will try the implementation with FV,
after a quick read of the code, the FV looks easier for me as well.
Nicolò
sounds good. FV already has slope limiters implemented in a utils, used in the MathFVUtils

I am at an early stage of this development and would appreciate your suggestion:
should I implement my previous transport laws into the FV framework,
or is there a simple way to retrofit my previous DG kernels with slope limiters?

If you're constraining yourself to at most a second order accurate (L2 norm) method, then I agree that FV is the easiest since it is the second order accurate reconstructed DG method. Did you have a reference for a particular slope limiter? It seems like maybe not

I have tried outputting the 2D MBB example first as a .vtk file in MOOSE, and then converting to a .msh file using Meshio in Python. Below is the .vtk file of the optimized component in Paraview:

Below is the resulting .msh file in Gmsh (created by converting the .vtk file to a .msh file w/ Meshio). As you can see, the .msh file is just the original rectangular domain, whereas I need it to exclude all of the void regions? Would I need to somehow create code that converts all element density values to 0 or 1, and then exclude all nodes in the mesh that are associated with void regions in the rectangular domain, before converting to an STL or MSH file type? Thanks in advance

Would I need to somehow create code that converts all element density values to 0 or 1, and then exclude all nodes in the mesh that are associated with void regions in the rectangular domain, before converting to an STL or MSH file type? Thanks in advance

this sounds like a good idea.
You can create a simulation that does just this:

load the output of the previous one
use a coupledVarThresholdSubdomainModifier to change the subdomain of the elements you want to get rid of

Save the result

load the output of that simulation
use the BlockDeletionGenerator to delete the elements in that new subdomain of the elements to get rid of

you can probably shorten this by executing coupledVarThresholdSubdomainModifier user object on FINAL at the end of your first simulation

There is a way to do this in Paraview. I don't remember the exact workflow but it's something like this. Use iso volume to threshold the density, then use the extract surface, then export as STL. I think the extract surface is needed but it's been a while.
Use cell data to point data to convert density to nodal values.

node.title: Seeking Advice on Setting Initial Conditions for Multi-Step Simulation in MOOSE
node.bodyText:
Hello everyone,
I'm conducting a simulation involving two steps. I'm encountering a problem of setting the initial conditions for step 2.
In step 1, I focused on variables such as A and B. In step 2, however, the variables shift to C and D, with C and D being the auxiliary variables from step 1.
I'm wondering if it's possible to use the auxiliary variables from step 1 as the initial conditions for the variables in step 2?
Thank you in advance for your time and assistance.
Best regards,
Xin

hello
We typically do not do this in a single application solve, though it could be done with a user object setting the initial condition of nonlinear variables. I think the better way to do this is with two solves in a multiapp setup.
See the documentation for the types of multiapps
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/syntax/MultiApps/index.html
and the tutorial on multiapps
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/getting_started/examples_and_tutorials/tutorial02_multiapps/presentation/index.html#/
Guillaume
Thank you for the advice!

Hi Guillaume,
I encountered a puzzling issue. When using parallel computing, I found that setting the number of parallel processes to 12 takes more wall time than when it's set to 4. I want to know what could be the possible reasons behind this, or do you have any suggestions regarding setting the parallel computing?
Thank you!
Best regards,
Xin

Hello
We recommend having at least 20k DoFs per process for the parallel communication costs in MOOSE to be outweighted by the computation costs. But some preconditioners will simply not scale to more than a few processes.
Having a solution method that solves the problem is a good first step, scaling to larger machines is a distinct piece of work
Guillaume
Thank you very much!

node.title: Convergence problem when using mortar based approach in contact calculation
node.bodyText:
Hello
I have ased the similar question when my geometry is 2D RZ coordinate in #27303.
I tried mortar approach in 3D situation but faced with convergence problem when it converged well in 2D simulation. There is no difference between two input files except mesh. There, https://github.com/jin0123456/miniature-system
When applied [gap_contact], it would run in a few time steps then became not converged. When applied [gap_contact1], it would not converge on the very first step.
So how to use 3D mortar based approach in the right way for my case?
@recuero @lindsayad

Many things could be happening. One thing I'd change right away is your solver settings. For example, to (Newton could work too):
  type = Transient
  solve_type = 'PJFNK'

  petsc_options = '-snes_ksp_ew'
  petsc_options_iname = '-pc_type -pc_factor_mat_solver_type -pc_factor_shift_type -pc_factor_shift_amount -mat_mffd_err'
  petsc_options_value = 'lu       superlu_dist                  NONZERO               1e-15                   1e-5'

I have run this type of problems in 3D, there shouldn't be a major problem. Also make sure sure you build with the appropriate automatic differentiation size, which I assume you are doing since you didn't get a error message to that effect.
Thanks for your advice. As many things could happen, I will try to find out the reason.

node.title: How to Utilize AD Stress Materials for the Homogenization system
node.bodyText:
I'm interested in applying AD stress materials to homogenization problems. It appears that there isn't an AD version available for the Lagrangian system. Are there any straightforward methods currently available to achieve this?
Alternatively, I've noticed methods like ComputeLagrangianWrappedStress. Perhaps converting AD stress materials to the Lagrangian system might be more convenient? However, I am unsure how to extract the pk1_jacobian from the AD stress material. Any guidance on this would be greatly appreciated.

Hello
The new Lagrangian system does not use AD.
You could try to convert your AD material property to regular material properties with this Material
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/source/materials/MaterialADConverter.html
and lose the derivatives. You ll get an imperfect Jacobian but you could work with PJFNK for the nonlinear solver
Guillaume

Thank you for the response, but it seems that MaterialADConverter may not address this issue. Both in the HomogenizationConstraint and TotalLagrangianStressDivergenceBase, which is the parent class of HomogenizedTotalLagrangianStressDivergence, the material pk1_jacobian is required:
HomogenizationConstraint::HomogenizationConstraint(const InputParameters & parameters)
  : ElementUserObject(parameters),
    _large_kinematics(getParam<bool>("large_kinematics")),
    _base_name(isParamValid("base_name") ? getParam<std::string>("base_name") + "_" : ""),
    _F(getMaterialPropertyByName<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "deformation_gradient")),
    _pk1_stress(getMaterialPropertyByName<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "pk1_stress")),
    _pk1_jacobian(getMaterialPropertyByName<RankFourTensor>(_base_name + "pk1_jacobian"))
{
  ...
}
template <class G>
TotalLagrangianStressDivergenceBase<G>::TotalLagrangianStressDivergenceBase(
    const InputParameters & parameters)
  : LagrangianStressDivergenceBase(parameters),
    _pk1(getMaterialPropertyByName<RankTwoTensor>(_base_name + "pk1_stress")),
    _dpk1(getMaterialPropertyByName<RankFourTensor>(_base_name + "pk1_jacobian"))
{
}
So, is there a method to explicitly extract pk1_jacobian as a material?
@hugary1995
AD is not currently not supported with the homogenization constraints. I will add an error check in the action.
